2	Ser vs. estar	<p>Remember to use <strong>estar</strong> to describe things that are only temporarily true, like the location of people and things.​</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/manuel.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Manuel <strong>est&aacute;</strong> aqu&iacute;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Manuel is here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You would also use <strong>estoy</strong>, <strong>est&aacute;s</strong>, <strong>est&aacute;</strong>, to talk about how people are feeling or doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/cansada.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iexcl;Yo <strong>estoy</strong> cansada!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I am tired!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use <strong>ser</strong> for more permanent descriptions, like explaining what someone is like.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/graduation.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi hermano <strong>es</strong> inteligente.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My brother is intelligent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You would also use <strong>soy</strong>, <strong>eres</strong>, <strong>es</strong> to say where people are from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/from-usa.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo <strong>soy</strong> de los Estados Unidos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I am from the United States.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Express Travel Needs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Tienes el boleto?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you have the ticket?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">S&iacute;, yo tengo el boleto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Yes, I have the ticket.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo necesito mi pasaporte.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I need my passport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Tienes la maleta?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you have the suitcase?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Necesita un taxi, se&ntilde;or?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you need a taxi, sir?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&iquest;Quieres m&aacute;s agua?</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember that in Spanish, verbs change depending on the person.</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>necesit<span><strong>o</strong></span> - need</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>necesit<span><strong>as</strong></span> - need</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>necesit<span><strong>a</strong></span> - needs / need</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notice that <strong>&eacute;l</strong>, <strong>ella</strong>, and <strong>usted</strong> always have the same verb form.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quier<span><strong>o</strong></span> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quier<span><strong>es</strong></span> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quier<span><strong>e</strong></span> - wants / want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n</table>		2024-11-22 21:12:59.893076+00	2024-12-02 12:37:08.812674+00	1	ser-vs-estar
9	Let's talk about Present Tense!	<p>Notice the three different patterns for verbs like <strong>habl<span>ar</span></strong>, <strong>com<span>er</span></strong>, or <strong>viv<span>ir</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Suject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (hablar)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<strong><span>o</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<strong><span>as</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<strong><span>a</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<strong><span>amos</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<strong><span>an</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Suject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (comer)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>o</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>es</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>e</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>emos</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>en</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Suject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (vivir)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>viv<strong><span>o</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>viv<strong><span>es</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>viv<strong><span>e</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>viv<strong><span>imos</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>viv<strong><span>en</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Describe activities</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotros trabajamos en casa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We work at home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">T&uacute; escribes bien en espa&ntilde;ol.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">You write well in Spanish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Ustedes aprenden italiano?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Are you learning Italian?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&Eacute;l quiere aprender italiano.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">He wants to learn Italian.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Happy endings</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The basic form of a verb is called an <strong>infinitive</strong>. For example, <strong>hablar (to speak)</strong>, <strong>comer (to eat)</strong>, and <strong>escribir (to write)</strong> are all infinitives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spanish has three verb groups: verbs ending in <strong><span>-ar</span></strong>, <strong><span>-er</span></strong>, or <strong><span>-ir</span></strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the ending patterns for each group.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (hablar)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>o</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>as</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>a</strong></span> - talks / speaks, talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>amos</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>an</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Suject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (comer)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>o</span></strong> - eat</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>es</span></strong> - eat</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>e</span></strong> - eats / eat</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>emos</span></strong> - eat</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>com<strong><span>en</span></strong> - eat</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (escribir)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>escrib<strong><span>o</span></strong> - write</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>escrib<strong><span>es</span></strong> - write</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>escrib<strong><span>e</span></strong> - writes / write</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>escrib<strong><span>imos</span></strong> - write</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>escri<strong><span>en</span></strong> - write</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>		2024-11-23 15:15:12.755351+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.5343+00	1	lets-talk-about-present-tense
3	Talk about schedules	<p class="spanish">Marco, &iquest;qu&eacute; d&iacute;a es hoy?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Marco, what day is today?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Hoy es jueves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Today is Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Cu&aacute;ndo es la fiesta?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">When is the party?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi fiesta de cumplea&ntilde;os es el s&aacute;bado.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My birthday party is on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Cu&aacute;ndo es el partido?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">When is the game?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El concierto es el s&aacute;bado.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The concert is on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Days of the week</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Spanish, the days of the week are not capitalized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Hoy es lunes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Today is Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To say <strong>on Monday</strong> or <strong>on Saturday</strong>, use <strong>el</strong> before the day of the week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/party.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">La fiesta es <strong>el</strong> viernes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The party is on Friday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Talk about your life</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Usted estudia franc&eacute;s?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you study French?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">No, yo no estudio franc&eacute;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">No, I do not study French.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;D&oacute;nde trabaja usted?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Where do you work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo trabajo en una f&aacute;brica.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I work in a factory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;D&oacute;nde vives?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Where do you live?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo vivo en Inglaterra.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I live in England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Spanish sounds</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&#39;s a difference between <strong>n</strong> and <strong>&ntilde;</strong>! A Spanish <strong>n</strong> is pronounced the same as the letter <strong>n</strong> in English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>n</strong>ecesito, ba<strong>n</strong>a<strong>n</strong>a - As in <strong>n</strong>est.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But <strong>&ntilde;</strong> is a little tricky! It almost sounds like <strong>ny</strong> in &ldquo;ca<strong>ny</strong>on&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ma<strong>&ntilde;</strong>ana, cumplea<strong>&ntilde;</strong>os - As in ca<strong>ny</strong>on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/canyon.jpg" width="400" /></p>		2024-11-22 21:43:53.895084+00	2024-12-02 12:38:25.928671+00	1	talk-about-schedules
4	Discuss others' lives	<p class="spanish">Bruno, &iquest;eres camarero?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Bruno, are you a waiter?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">No, Carmen es camarera.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">No, Carmen is a waitress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El maestro es mexicano.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The teacher is Mexican.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">La maestra es cubana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The teacher is Cuban.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Jos&eacute;, &iquest;tu hermano es m&eacute;dico?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Jose, is your brother a doctor?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">No, mi hermana es m&eacute;dica.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">No, my sister is a doctor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&iexcl;Yo soy estudiante!</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In English, we say <strong>I am a teacher</strong>, but in Spanish, you don&#39;t need to use <strong>a</strong> when talking about occupations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/doctor.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi hermana es m&eacute;dica.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My sister is a doctor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/professor.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi amigo es profesor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My friend is a professor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Talk about college</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Ella estudia espa&ntilde;ol en la universidad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">She studies Spanish at the university.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;La universidad tiene tres bibliotecas?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Does the university have three libraries?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Ana, &iquest;la biblioteca tiene computadoras?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Ana, does the library have computers?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">S&iacute;, la biblioteca tiene dos computadoras.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Yes, the library has two computers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Eduardo, &iquest;necesitas este libro?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Eduardo, do you need this book?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi clase tiene siete estudiantes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My class has seven students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>Este vs. esta</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Spanish, the word for <strong>this</strong> changes depending on the gender of the noun it goes with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/book.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>Este</strong> libr<strong>o</strong> es divertido.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">This book is fun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/library.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo trabajo en <strong>esta</strong> bibliotec<strong>a</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I work in this library.</p>		2024-11-22 22:13:04.643201+00	2024-12-02 12:40:38.489939+00	1	discuss-others-lives
5	Let's talk about Agreement	<p>Words describing a noun should agree, or match, in their gender.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>un</strong> ni&ntilde;<strong>o</strong> mexican<strong>o</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>el</strong> ni&ntilde;<strong>o</strong> american<strong>o</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>una</strong> ni&ntilde;<strong>a</strong> mexican<strong>a</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>la</strong> ni&ntilde;<strong>a</strong> american<strong>a</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Describe your family</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo tengo una familia peque&ntilde;a.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I have a small family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi esposa se llama Amanda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My wife&#39;s name is Amanda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Tienes hijos?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you have children?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">S&iacute;, mi hijo se llama Alberto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Yes, my son&#39;s name is Alberto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Mi hija Camila tiene cinco a&ntilde;os.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My daughter Camila is five years old.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>AGE</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In English, we say <strong>I am sixteen years old</strong>. But in Spanish, you&#39;d say <strong>I have sixteen years.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/baby.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El beb&eacute; <strong>tiene</strong> un a&ntilde;o</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The baby is one year old.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/boy.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo <strong>tengo</strong> ocho a&ntilde;os.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I am eight years old.</p>		2024-11-22 22:36:02.040552+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.53857+00	1	lets-talk-about-agreement
6	Talk about office work	<p class="spanish">Ana trabaja con los secretarios.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Ana works with the secretaries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&Eacute;l trabaja mucho los lunes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">He works a lot on Mondays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Ella escribe un mensaje para el jefe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">She is writing a message for the boss.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El jefe lee los mensajes ahora.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The boss is reading the messages now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Este mensaje es para la jefa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">This message is for the boss.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Los and las</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When referring to more than one person or thing, <strong>el</strong> becomes <strong>los</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/pen.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">el bol&iacute;grafo</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the pen</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/pens.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>los</strong> bol&iacute;grafo<strong>s</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the pens</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And <strong>la</strong> becomes <strong>las</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/letter.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">la carta</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/letters.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>las</strong> carta<strong>s</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the letters</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What&#39;s the deal with su?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Su</strong> can mean a few different things! Context will help you understand which meaning is intended!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/money.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>su</strong> dinero</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><strong>her</strong> money</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/business.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>su</strong> negocio</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><strong>their</strong> business</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/man-sell-coffee.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iexcl;<strong>Su</strong> caf&eacute;, se&ntilde;or!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><strong>Your</strong> coffee, sir!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Describe emotions</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Hola pap&aacute;, &iquest;c&oacute;mo est&aacute;s?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Hi dad, how are you?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Estoy cansado y quiero dormir.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I&#39;m tired and I want to sleep.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Estoy muy preocupado hoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I am very worried today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iexcl;Yo tambi&eacute;n!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Me too!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;C&oacute;mo te sientes hoy?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">How do you feel today?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo no me siento muy bien hoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I don&#39;t feel very well today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&iexcl;Me siento enfermo!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some Spanish verbs like <strong>me llamo</strong> and <strong>te sientes</strong> always need an extra little word before them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/my-name-is-julia.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>Me</strong> llamo Julia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">My name is Julia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/how-do-you-feel.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;C&oacute;mo <strong>te</strong> sientes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">How do you feel?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/boy-and-man.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Se&ntilde;or, c&oacute;mo <strong>se</strong> llama usted?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Sir, what is your name?</p>		2024-11-22 22:46:19.357301+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.53996+00	1	talk-about-office-work
7	Say where people are from	<p class="tip">Nosotros no somos de M&eacute;xico.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are not from Mexico.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotras no hablamos portugu&eacute;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We don&#39;t speak Portuguese.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Los hombres son de Francia?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Are the men from France?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Las mujeres son de los Estados Unidos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The women are from the United States.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotros somos de la ciudad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are from the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Ellos son los hombres de Nueva York?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Are they the men from New York?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nosotras hablamos espa&ntilde;ol</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Remember that verbs change depending on the person. They also change when there is more than one person!</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (hablar)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>o</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>as</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>a</strong></span> - talks / speaks, talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>amos</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>habl<span><strong>an</strong></span> - talk / speak</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>To be or not to be? </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The verb <strong>ser</strong> is very special! It has its own forms and it doesn&#39;t follow the regular patterns.</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (ser)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>soy - am</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>eres - are</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>es - is / are</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>somos - are</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>son - are</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Describe clothing</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo estoy contento con mis zapatos nuevos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I am happy with my new shoes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;T&uacute; tienes un vestido rojo?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you have a red dress?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Qui&eacute;n usa pantalones verdes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Who wears green pants?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Sonia, t&uacute; tienes unas carteras bonitas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Sonia, you have some pretty purses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Juan necesita muchas camisetas verdes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Juan needs a lot of green t-shirts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Zapatos verdes</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add <span><strong>-s</strong></span> to <strong>both</strong> the adjective <strong>and</strong> the noun if a word is plural!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/shoe.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">el zapato verde</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the green shoe</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/green-shoes.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong>los</strong> zapato<strong>s</strong> verde<strong>s</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">the green shoes</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Mi vs. mis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In English, we say <strong>my shirt</strong> and <strong>my shirts</strong>. But in Spanish, if there is more than one shirt, you would add <span><strong>‑s</strong></span> also to words like <strong>my, your</strong> and <strong>her</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/t-shirt.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">mi / tu / su + camisa</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">my / your / his / her + shirt</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/t-shirts.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">mi<span><strong>s</strong></span> / tu<span><strong>s</strong></span> / su<span><strong>s</strong></span> + camisa<span><strong>s</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">my / your + shirts</p>		2024-11-23 14:31:46.325027+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.541264+00	1	say-where-people-are-from
8	Ask for directions	<p class="spanish">Perd&oacute;n, &iquest;d&oacute;nde est&aacute; la estaci&oacute;n de tren?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Excuse me, where is the train station?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">La estaci&oacute;n est&aacute; cerca del hotel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The station is close to the hotel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El hotel est&aacute; lejos de la parada del autob&uacute;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The hotel is far from the bus stop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotros estamos al lado del caf&eacute;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are next to the caf&eacute;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;El hotel est&aacute; a la derecha o a la izquierda?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Is the hotel to the right or to the left?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">A la derecha.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">To the right.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&iquest;D&oacute;nde est&aacute;s?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You already saw how <strong>estar</strong> can be used to describe temporary conditions. You can also use <strong>estar</strong> to talk about the location of places, objects, or people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/in-the-park.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotras estamos en el parque.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are in the park.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/hospital.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El hospital est&aacute; en la ciudad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The hospital is in the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Al and del</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Spanish, you never say <strong>de el</strong>. Instead, these words are combined together into <span><strong>del</strong></span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/coffee-shop.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Estamos cerca <strong>del</strong> caf&eacute; ahora.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are close to the cafe now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Similarly, <strong>a</strong> and <strong>el</strong> are always combined together into <span><strong>al</strong></span>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/airport.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Quiero ir <strong>al</strong> aeropuerto en la ma&ntilde;ana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I want to go to the airport in the morning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But <strong>de</strong> and <strong>a</strong> don&#39;t combine with <strong>la</strong>, <strong>los</strong>, or <strong>las</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Estamos cerca de la calle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We are close to the street.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Por qu&eacute; no quieres ir a los parques?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Why don&#39;t you want to go to the parks?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Talk about free time</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotras queremos unas vacaciones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We want a vacation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Renato y yo queremos caminar en la playa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Renato and I want to walk on the beach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo quiero caminar con mi perro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I want to walk with my dog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Nosotros siempre leemos en las vacaciones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">We always read on vacation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Ellos comen con amigos los fines de semana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">They eat with friends on the weekends.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iexcl;Qu&eacute; bueno!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">How good!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Stem-changing verbs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In some Spanish verbs, the middle vowel changes. For example, we say <strong>qu<span>e</span>rer</strong>, but <strong>yo qu<span>ie</span>ro</strong> and <strong>&eacute;l qu<span>ie</span>re</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the so-called <strong>e-to-ie</strong> verbs. But watch out! The <strong>e</strong> doesn&#39;t change in the <strong>nosotros / nosotras</strong> form.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (querer)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong>qu<span>ie</span>ro</strong> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong>qu<span>ie</span>res</strong> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong>qu<span>ie</span>re</strong> - wants / want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong>queremos</strong> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong>qu<span>ie</span>ren</strong> - want</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>		2024-11-23 14:45:48.957018+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.542853+00	1	ask-for-directions
10	Express preferences	<p class="spanish">Me encanta la m&uacute;sica de Enrique.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I love Enrique&#39;s music.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Carmen, &iquest;te gusta nadar?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Carmen, do you like to swim?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">No, no me gusta nadar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">No, I do not like to swim.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Te gusta jugar al f&uacute;tbol?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you like to play soccer?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Me gusta la bicicleta de Mateo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I like Mateo&#39;s bicycle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Me gusta el espa&ntilde;ol!</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In English, we say <strong>I like chocolate</strong>, but in Spanish you&#39;d say something more like <strong>To me chocolate is pleasing</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/chocolate.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Me gusta el chocolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I like chocolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/swimming-pool.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Te gusta nadar en la piscina?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you like swimming in the pool?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>La bicicleta de Matthew</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In English, we say <strong>Matthew<span>&#39;s</span></strong> bicycle to show that the bicycle belongs to Matthew. But in Spanish, you&#39;d say <strong>la bicicleta <span>de</span> Matthew</strong>, which literally means <strong>the bicycle of Matthew</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/bicycle.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">La bicicleta <strong><span>de</span></strong> Matthew es roja.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Matthew&#39;s bicycle is red.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english"><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/red-dress.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">El vestido <strong><span>de</span></strong> Sandra es muy elegante.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Sandra&#39;s dress is very elegant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Describe your routine</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;A qu&eacute; hora te levantas?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">What time do you get up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Los domingos me levanto a las doce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">On Sundays I get up at noon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Tienes que trabajar los s&aacute;bados?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you have to work on Saturdays?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">S&iacute;, a menudo tengo que trabajar los s&aacute;bados.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Yes, I often have to work on Saturdays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo nunca estudio los domingos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I never study on Sundays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Yo estudio espa&ntilde;ol todos los d&iacute;as.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I study Spanish every day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Special verbs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some common verbs, like <span>ir</span> don&#39;t follow the regular patterns we&#39;ve seen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Verb (ir)</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>yo - I</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><span>voy</span> - go</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>t&uacute; - you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><span>vas</span> - go</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&eacute;l / ella / usted - he / she / you</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><span>va</span> - goes / go</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>nosotros / nosotras - we</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><span>vamos</span> - go</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>ellos / ellas / ustedes - they / you all</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><span>van</span> - go</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>		2024-11-23 15:19:44.450498+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.54457+00	1	express-preferences
11	Describe your home	<p class="spanish">Estas salas son muy modernas y bonitas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">These living rooms are very modern and pretty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Las habitaciones son grandes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">The bedrooms are big.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Hay dos estanter&iacute;as en mi dormitorio.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">There are two bookcases in my bedroom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Esos ba&ntilde;os no son modernos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Those bathrooms are not modern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">No hay sillas en la cocina.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">There are no chairs in the kitchen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Ese vs. esa</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Spanish, the word for <strong>that</strong> changes depending on the gender of the noun it goes with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/bedroom.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">es<strong><span>e</span></strong> dormitori<strong><span>o</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">that bedroom</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/fridge.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">es<strong><span>a</span></strong> never<strong><span>a</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">that fridge</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The word for <strong>those</strong> changes depending on gender as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/bathrooms.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">eso<strong><span>os</span></strong> ba&ntilde;<strong><span>os</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">those bathrooms</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/four-t-shirts.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">esa<strong><span>as</span></strong> camis<strong><span>as</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">those shirts</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nouns ending in <strong><span>-o</span></strong> are usually masculine, and nouns ending in <strong><span>-a</span></strong> are usually feminine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But what about words that end in consonants? Luckily, most of them are still predictable!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>masculine</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>feminine</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>el</span></strong> hospita<strong><span>l</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>la</span></strong> pare<strong><span>d</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>el</span></strong> tenedo<strong><span>r</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>la</span></strong> habita<strong><span>ci&oacute;n</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>la</span></strong> televi<strong><span>si&oacute;n</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>la</span></strong> cost<strong><span>umbre</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td><strong><span>la</span></strong> lu<strong><span>z</span></strong></td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, languages and days of the week are always masculine, no matter what letter they end with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>el</span></strong> espa&ntilde;ol</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Spanish</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>el</span></strong> ingl&eacute;s</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">English</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>el</span></strong> lunes</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Monday</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>el</span></strong> s&aacute;bado</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Saturday</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip"><strong>KEY PHRASES - Order at a restaurant</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Puede traer el men&uacute;, por favor?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Can you bring the menu, please?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Qu&eacute; bebidas quieren ustedes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">What drinks do you want?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Dos cervezas, por favor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Two beers, please.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Quisiera pollo con ensalada.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I would like chicken with salad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">&iquest;Quieren comer postre?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">Do you want to eat dessert?</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish">Quisiera el pastel de chocolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I would like the chocolate cake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="tip">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Quisiera</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A polite way to ask for something in Spanish is <strong><span>quisiera</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/22/man-sell-coffee.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>Quisiera</span></strong> un caf&eacute; sin az&uacute;car.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I would like a coffee without sugar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" height="200" src="/media/images/lessons/2024/11/23/another-wine.jpg" width="400" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="spanish"><strong><span>Quisiera</span></strong> otra bebida, por favor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="english">I would like another drink, please.</p>		2024-11-23 15:39:13.667267+00	2024-11-29 19:48:25.546301+00	1	describe-your-home
