15	Modo Subjuntivo	<p>The <strong>Subjunctive Mood (Modo Subjuntivo)</strong> in Spanish is used to express uncertainty, wishes, emotions, hypothetical situations, or actions that have not yet occurred. Unlike the indicative mood, which states facts or truths, the subjunctive expresses subjective or non-concrete ideas.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>When to Use the Subjunctive</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The subjunctive is commonly used in the following situations:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Wishes or Desires:</strong> When expressing something you want or hope for.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Espero que t&uacute; <em>vengas</em> ma&ntilde;ana.&quot; (I hope you come tomorrow.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Emotions:</strong> When expressing feelings or emotions about something.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Me alegra que ellos <em>est&eacute;n</em> aqu&iacute;.&quot; (I&#39;m glad they are here.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Uncertainty or Doubt:</strong> When there is doubt or lack of certainty.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;No creo que &eacute;l <em>sepa</em> la respuesta.&quot; (I don&#39;t think he knows the answer.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Hypothetical Situations:</strong> When describing hypothetical or uncertain outcomes.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Si yo <em>fuera</em> t&uacute;, hablar&iacute;a con ella.&quot; (If I were you, I would talk to her.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pending Actions:</strong> When talking about actions that have not yet happened.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Te llamar&eacute; cuando <em>llegues</em>.&quot; (I will call you when you arrive.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>How to Form the Subjunctive</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The subjunctive mood is formed by modifying the endings of the present tense verbs. Here&#39;s how:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Start with the <strong>yo form</strong> of the present indicative.</li>\r\n\t<li>Drop the <strong>-o</strong> ending.</li>\r\n\t<li>Add the appropriate subjunctive ending.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Subjunctive Endings</h4>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subject</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>-AR Verbs</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>-ER / -IR Verbs</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-e</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-a</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>T&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-es</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-as</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&Eacute;l/Ella/Usted</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-e</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-a</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Nosotros/as</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-emos</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-amos</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Vosotros/as</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-&eacute;is</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-&aacute;is</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Ellos/Ellas/Ustedes</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-en</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>-an</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Irregular Verbs</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some verbs are irregular in the subjunctive. Here are common examples:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Ser:</strong> sea, seas, sea, seamos, se&aacute;is, sean</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Estar:</strong> est&eacute;, est&eacute;s, est&eacute;, estemos, est&eacute;is, est&eacute;n</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Ir:</strong> vaya, vayas, vaya, vayamos, vay&aacute;is, vayan</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Saber:</strong> sepa, sepas, sepa, sepamos, sep&aacute;is, sepan</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Haber:</strong> haya, hayas, haya, hayamos, hay&aacute;is, hayan</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Practice Exercises</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fill in the blanks with the correct