19	Comparación: "LLEVAR" vs "LLEVARSE"	<p>The verbs <strong>&quot;llevar&quot;</strong> and <strong>&quot;llevarse&quot;</strong> are closely related but have different meanings and uses in Spanish. Understanding the distinction between them will help you communicate more effectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>1. The Verb &quot;Llevar&quot;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Llevar&quot; is a non-reflexive verb and generally means:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>To carry or transport:</strong> Refers to physically taking something or someone to another place.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Yo <em>llevo</em> mi mochila al trabajo.&quot; (I take my backpack to work.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>To wear:</strong> Refers to the clothes or accessories a person is wearing.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Hoy <em>llevo</em> un vestido azul.&quot; (Today I&rsquo;m wearing a blue dress.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>To indicate time or progress:</strong> Used to describe how long something has been happening.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Ellos <em>llevan</em> dos a&ntilde;os viviendo aqu&iacute;.&quot; (They&rsquo;ve been living here for two years.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n\t<li>\r\n\t<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>2. The Verb &quot;Llevarse&quot;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Llevarse&quot; is a reflexive form of &quot;llevar&quot; and is used in these contexts:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>To take something away:</strong> Refers to taking something for oneself or removing it.\r\n\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Ella se <em>llev&oacute;</em> todos los libros.&quot; (She took all the books.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>To get along (well or poorly):</strong> Describes the relationship between two or