16	El verbo "QUEDAR"	<p>The verb <strong>&quot;quedar&quot;</strong> is highly versatile in Spanish and has different meanings depending on the context. It can be used to talk about location, agreements, remaining quantities, appearance, or how something suits someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Meanings of &quot;Quedar&quot;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>1. To Remain or Be Left</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedar&quot; is used to express what remains or is left of something.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Solo <em>quedan</em> dos entradas para el concierto.&quot; (Only two tickets are left for the concert.)</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>2. To Arrange to Meet</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedar&quot; is used to talk about making plans or arrangements with someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Hemos <em>quedado</em> con Ana a las 7 en el caf&eacute;.&quot; (We arranged to meet Ana at 7 at the caf&eacute;.)</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>3. To Fit or Suit</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedar&quot; is used to describe how clothes fit or look on someone.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Esa camisa te <em>queda</em> muy bien.&quot; (That shirt suits you well.)</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>4. To Stay in a Place</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedar&quot; is used to indicate that someone is staying in a location.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Nos <em>quedamos</em> en casa durante el fin de semana.&quot; (We stayed at home over the weekend.)</div>\r\n\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>5. To Be Located</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedar&quot; is used to talk about the location of a place.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;&iquest;D&oacute;nde <em>queda</em> el museo?&quot; (Where is the museum located?)</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Conjugation of &quot;Quedar&quot; in Present Tense</h4>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Pronoun</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Conjugation</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quedo</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>T&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quedas</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&Eacute;l/Ella/Usted</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>queda</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Nosotros/as</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quedamos</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Vosotros/as</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>qued&aacute;is</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Ellos/Ellas/Ustedes</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>quedan</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Common Expressions with &quot;Quedar&quot;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>&quot;Quedarse en casa&quot;:</strong> To stay at home.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>&quot;Quedar con alguien&quot;:</strong> To meet up with someone.</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>&quot;Quedar bien/mal&quot;:</strong> To look good/bad (usually referring to clothing).</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>&quot;Quedarse sin algo&quot;:</strong> To run out of something.\r\n\t<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Nos hemos <em>quedado</em> sin leche.&quot; (We ran out of milk.)</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>&quot;&iquest;D&oacute;nde queda...?&quot;:</strong> Where is ... located?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Practice Exercises</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fill in the blanks with the correct form of &quot;quedar&quot;:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>Solo (quedar) __________ cinco minutos para terminar la clase.</li>\r\n\t<li>Nosotros (quedar) __________ con Juan para cenar.</li>\r\n\t<li>Esa chaqueta te (quedar) __________ perfecta.</li>\r\n\t<li>&iquest;(Quedar) __________ lejos la estaci&oacute;n de tren?</li>\r\n\t<li>Me (quedar) __________ en casa porque est&aacute; lloviendo.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="see-answers"><input id="toggle-answers" type="checkbox" /> <label class="toggle-label" for="toggle-answers"><strong>Answers</strong></labe