13	Concordancia de los tiempos verbales en Plan pasado.	<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Spanish, the &quot;concordancia de los tiempos verbales&quot; refers to the agreement of verb tenses between the main clause and the subordinate clause. When talking about the past (plan pasado), specific rules apply to ensure the correct use of tenses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Rules for Concordance</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the main clause is in the past tense (e.g., pret&eacute;rito or imperfecto), the subordinate clause usually takes a verb tense that logically follows the time frame. The following table shows common scenarios:</p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Main Clause (Past Tense)</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Subordinate Clause (Tense)</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Example</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Preterite (Pret&eacute;rito)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Imperfect Subjunctive (Subjuntivo Imperfecto)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Ella dijo que estudiara.&quot;</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Imperfect (Imperfecto)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Imperfect Subjunctive (Subjuntivo Imperfecto)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Pensaba que vinieras temprano.&quot;</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Pluperfect (Pluscuamperfecto)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Pluperfect Subjunctive (Pluscuamperfecto de Subjuntivo)</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Hab&iacute;a pensado que hubieras llegado antes.&quot;</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Common Structures</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are the most common structures where concordance of tenses in the past is applied:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Indirect Speech (Estilo indirecto):</strong> When reporting what someone said in the past.\r\n\r\n\t<div class="example">Example: &quot;&Eacute;l dijo que <em>quer&iacute;a</em> salir temprano.&quot;</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div class="example">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Hypothetical Situations (Hip&oacute;tesis):</strong> When imagining or hypothesizing about the past.\r\n\r\n\t<div class="example">Example: &quot;Si <em>hubieras estudiado</em>, habr&iacute;as aprobado.&quot;</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div class="example">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Purpose Clauses (Finalidad):</strong> When expressing a purpose or intention in the past.\r\n\r\n\t<div class="example">Example: &quot;Estudi&eacute; para que <em>entendieras</em> mejor.&quot;</div>\r\n\t</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Practice Exercises</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Complete the sentences below with the correct verb form to ensure proper concordance:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>&quot;Ella me dijo que (venir) __________ a tiempo.&quot;</li>\r\n\t<li>&quot;Si (saber) __________ antes, habr&iacute;a cambiado mis planes.&quot;</li>\r\n\t<li>&quot;Pensaban que (ser) __________ una buena idea.&quot;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="see-answers"><input id="toggle-answers" type="checkbox" /> <label class="toggle-label" for="toggle-answers"><strong>Answers</strong></label>\r\n\r\n<ol class="answers-list">\r\n\t<li>1. viniera</li>\r\n\t<li>2. hubiera sabido</li>\r\n\t<li>3. era</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mastering the concordance of verb tenses in the past is essential for clear and accurate communication in Spanish. Practice with different examples and pay attention to how native speakers use these structures.</p>		2024-11-29 08:12:20.761091+00	2024-12-02 11:57:46.541933+00	2	concordancia-de-los-tiempos-verbales-en-plan-pasado
20	Comparación: Pretérito Perfecto de Indicativo vs Pretérito Indefinido	<p>Both <strong>Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto de Indicativo</strong> and <strong>Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido</strong> are used to talk about the past in Spanish, but they are used in different contexts. Understanding their distinctions is key to expressing yourself correctly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>1. Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto de Indicativo</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tense is used to talk about actions or events that are connected to the present. It is often translated as &quot;have/has done&quot; in English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Form:</h4>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Haber (present tense) + past participle</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Yo:</strong> he hablado</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>T&uacute;:</strong> has hablado</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>&Eacute;l/Ella/Usted:</strong> ha hablado</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Nosotros/as:</strong> hemos hablado</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Vosotros/as:</strong> hab&eacute;is hablado</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Ellos/Ellas/Ustedes:</strong> han hablado</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h4>When to Use Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto:</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Actions connected to the present:</strong> &quot;Hoy he comido una pizza.&quot; (Today I have eaten a pizza.)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Life experiences:</strong> &quot;&iquest;Alguna vez has viajado a Espa&ntilde;a?&quot; (Have you ever traveled to Spain?)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Recent past:</strong> &quot;Esta semana hemos estudiado mucho.&quot; (This week we have studied a lot.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>2. Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This tense is used to describe completed actions or events in the past with no connection to the present. It is often translated as &quot;did&quot; in English.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Form:</h4>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Root + past tense endings</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>-AR verbs:</strong> habl&eacute;, hablaste, habl&oacute;, hablamos, hablasteis, hablaron</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>-ER/-IR verbs:</strong> com&iacute;, comiste, comi&oacute;, comimos, comisteis, comieron</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>When to Use Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido:</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Completed actions in the past:</strong> &quot;Ayer com&iacute; una pizza.&quot; (Yesterday I ate a pizza.)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Actions with a specific time frame:</strong> &quot;El a&ntilde;o pasado viajamos a M&eacute;xico.&quot; (Last year we traveled to Mexico.)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Sequential past actions:</strong> &quot;Llegu&eacute;, vi y venc&iacute;.&quot; (I came, I saw, I conquered.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Key Differences</h4>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Aspect</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Time Frame</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Actions connected to the present.</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Completed actions in the past with no connection to the present.</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Keywords</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Hoy, esta semana, este a&ntilde;o, alguna vez.</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Ayer, anoche, el a&ntilde;o pasado, en 1990.</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Examples</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;He hablado con ella hoy.&quot;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&quot;Habl&eacute; con ella ayer.&quot;</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Examples Comparing Both Tenses</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto:</strong> &quot;Esta ma&ntilde;ana <em>he desayunado</em> temprano.&quot; (This morning I have had breakfast early.)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido:</strong> &quot;Ayer <em>desayun&eacute;</em> tarde.&quot; (Yesterday I had breakfast late.)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto:</strong> &quot;&iquest;Alguna vez <em>has visitado</em> Espa&ntilde;a?&quot; (Have you ever visited Spain?)</li>\r\n\t<li><strong>Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido:</strong> &quot;El a&ntilde;o pasado <em>visit&eacute;</em> Espa&ntilde;a.&quot; (Last year I visited Spain.)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Practice Exercises</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Complete the sentences with the correct form of the verb in Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto or Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>(Comer) __________ pizza hoy.</li>\r\n\t<li>(Visitar) __________ Barcelona el a&ntilde;o pasado.</li>\r\n\t<li>Esta semana (hacer) __________ mucho trabajo.</li>\r\n\t<li>(Hablar) __________ con mi jefe ayer.</li>\r\n\t<li>&iquest;Alguna vez (ver) __________ esta pel&iacute;cula?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<div class="see-answers">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="see-answers"><input id="toggle-answers" type="checkbox" /> <label class="toggle-label" for="toggle-answers"><strong>Answers</strong></label>\r\n\r\n<ol class="answers-list">\r\n\t<li>He comido</li>\r\n\t<li>Visit&eacute;</li>\r\n\t<li>He hecho</li>\r\n\t<li>Habl&eacute;</li>\r\n\t<li>Has visto</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Conclusion</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The difference between Pret&eacute;rito Perfecto and Pret&eacute;rito Indefinido lies in their connection to the present and their focus on time frames. Practice using these tenses in context to gain confidence in their use.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>		2024-12-05 12:08:25.158327+00	2024-12-05 12:12:50.975534+00	2	comparacion-preterito-perfecto-de-indicativo-vs-preterito-indefinido
17	El verbo "QUEDARSE"	<p>The verb <strong>&quot;quedarse&quot;</strong> is a reflexive form of &quot;quedar,&quot; and its meaning changes depending on the context. It is commonly used to express staying in a place, retaining something, or changes in states or conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Meanings of &quot;Quedarse&quot;</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>1. To Stay in a Place</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedarse&quot; is used to indicate that someone is staying in a specific location, either temporarily or permanently.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Nos <em>quedamos</em> en un hotel durante las vacaciones.&quot; (We stayed in a hotel during the holidays.)</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>2. To Keep or Retain</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedarse&quot; can be used to indicate keeping something for oneself.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Me <em>quedo</em> con este libro.&quot; (I&rsquo;ll keep this book.)</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>3. To Be Left or Run Out of Something</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>It can also express the idea of being left without something.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Nos <em>quedamos</em> sin gasolina.&quot; (We ran out of gas.)</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>4. To Express a Change of State</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Quedarse&quot; is often used to describe a sudden or lasting change in a person&rsquo;s state or condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<div><strong>Example:</strong> &quot;Ella se <em>qued&oacute;</em> sorprendida con la noticia.&quot; (She was surprised by the news.)</div>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4>Conjugation of &quot;Quedarse&quot; in Present Tense</h4>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n\t<thead>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Pronoun</th>\r\n\t\t\t<th>Conjugation</th>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t</thead>\r\n\t<tbody>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>Yo</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>me quedo</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>T&uacute;</td>\r\n\t\t\t<td>te quedas</td>\r\n\t\t</tr>\r\n\t\t<tr>\r\n\t\t\t<td>&Eacute;l